‚Äú$$‚Äù is a useful Linux variable you could use in your script to get it‚Äôs PID. The ‚Äú$$‚Äù variable always holds the PID of the executing process.
Why do you need it? Maybe to check if the script is already running? This is what I normally use it for.
Sample Script;
#!/bin/bash&lt;br /&gt; echo &quot;My PID is $$&quot;&lt;br /&gt; sleep 2
Sample Output;
[root@keke ~]# ./test1.sh&lt;br /&gt; My PID is 8909

Was helping a friend fix his php script today. He was not too sure about what ‚Äúdirname(__FILE__)‚Äù did.
dirname() is a PHP function which returns the directory name of a file. For example if file abc.txt was in ‚Äú/tmp/abc.txt‚Äù then the dirname() function would return ‚Äú/tmp‚Äù .
Example Usage;
&lt;?php
$file = ‚Äú/tmp/abc.txt‚Äù;
$path = dirname($file); // $path will now contain /tmp
?&gt;
What does dirname(__FILE__) and basename(dirname(__FILE__)) do then?

